516b\u5e61\u5e73\u5e02|Hachimantai-shi}} is a [[Cities of Japan|city]] located in [[Iwate Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. {{As of|2020|04|01}}, the city had an estimated [[population]] of 25,076, and a [[population density]] of 29 persons per km\u00b2 in 10,531 households.<ref>[https://www.city.hachimantai.lg.jp/soshiki/shiminka/1552.html Hachimantai city official statistics]</ref> The total area of the city is {{convert|862.30|sqkm|sqmi}}.\n\n==Geography==\nHachimantai is located in the [[\u014cu Mountains]] of far northwest Iwate Prefecture, bordered by [[Aomori Prefecture]] to the north and [[Akita Prefecture]] to the west. The headwaters of the [[Yoneshiro River]] are in Hachimanai. Part of [[Mount Hachimantai]] and [[Mount Iwate]] are within its borders. Parts of the city are within the borders of the [[Towada-Hachimantai National Park]]. [[Mount Iwate]], the highest mountain in Iwate Prefecture, is on the border of Hachimantai with Shizukuishi and Takizawa.\n\n===Neighboring municipalities===\nAomori Prefecture\n*[[Takko, Aomori|Takko]]\nAkita Prefecture\n*[[Kazuno, Akita|Kazuno]]\n*[[Semboku, Akita|Semboku]]\nIwate Prefecture\n*[[Morioka, Iwate|Morioka]]\n*[[Ninohe, Iwate|Ninohe]]\n*[[Takizawa, Iwate|Takizawa]]\n*[[Ichinohe, Iwate|Ichinohe]]\n*[[Iwate, Iwate|Iwate]]\n*[[Shizukuishi, Iwate|Shizukuishi]]\n\n===Climate===\nHachimantai has a [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dfa''), the same as much of [[Hokkaido]] to the north, characterized by mild summers and cold winters with heavy snowfall. The average annual temperature in Hachimantai is 9.3&nbsp;\u00b0C. The average annual rainfall is 1387&nbsp;mm with September as the wettest month and February as the driest month. The temperatures are highest on average in August, at around 22.9&nbsp;\u00b0C, and lowest in January, at around -3.4&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref>[https://en.climate-data.org/location/5525/ Hachimantai climate data]</ref>\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n|location = Hachimantai (former Matsuo Village\u30011981-2010)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 12.4\n|Feb record high C = 12.0\n|Mar record high C = 18.0\n|Apr record high C = 27.7\n|May record high C = 31.8\n|Jun record high C = 33.5\n|Jul record high C = 35.2\n|Aug record high C = 35.5\n|Sep record high C = 34.0\n|Oct record high C = 26.5\n|Nov record high C = 20.7\n|Dec record high C = 16.9\n|Jan high C = 0.6\n|Feb high C = 1.6\n|Mar high C = 5.7\n|Apr high C = 13.7 \n|May high C = 19.3\n|Jun high C = 23.3\n|Jul high C = 26.2\n|Aug high C = 27.8\n|Sep high C = 22.9\n|Oct high C = 16.9\n|Nov high C = 9.7\n|Dec high C = 3.6\n|year high C = 14.2\n|Jan mean C = -3.4\n|Feb mean C = -2.8\n|Mar mean C = 0.9\n|Apr mean C = 7.6\n|May mean C = 13.3\n|Jun mean C = 17.6\n|Jul mean C = 21.1\n|Aug mean C = 22.4\n|Sep mean C = 17.5\n|Oct mean C = 10.9\n|Nov mean C = 4.7\n|Dec mean C = -0.3\n|year mean C = 9.1\n|Jan low C = -8.4\n|Feb low C = -8.0\n|Mar low C = -4.2\n|Apr low C = 1.3\n|May low C = 7.2\n|Jun low C = 12.6\n|Jul low C = 16.9\n|Aug low C = 18.1\n|Sep low C = 12.7\n|Oct low C = 5.2\n|Nov low C = -0.2\n|Dec low C = -4.5\n|year low C = 4.0\n|Jan record low C =-21.8\n|Feb record low C =-22.2\n|Mar record low C =-15.4\n|Apr record low C =-11.0\n|May record low C =-2.7\n|Jun record low C =1.7\n|Jul record low C =7.7\n|Aug record low C =7.7\n|Sep record low C =1.3\n|Oct record low C =-4.3\n|Nov record low C =-11.0\n|Dec record low C =-18.0\n|year record low C =-22.2\n|source 1 = [[Japan Meteorological Agency]]<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.data.jma.go.jp/obd/stats/etrn/view/nml_amd_ym.php?prec_no=33&block_no=0214&year=&month=&day=&view=\n| title = \u5ca9\u624b\u677e\u5c3e\uff08\u516b\u5e61\u5e73\uff09 19801-2010\u5e74 | accessdate = 2011-10-18 | publisher = Japan Meteorological Agency}}</ref>\n|date= November 2013}}\n\n==Demographics==\nPer Japanese census data,<ref>[https://www.citypopulation.de/Japan-Iwate.html Hachimantai population statistics]</ref> the population of Hachimantai peaked at around the year 1950 and has declined steadily over the past 60 years.\n{{Historical populations\n| 1920 | 21,815\n| 1930 | 27,328\n| 1940 | 36,316\n| 1950 | 47,852\n| 1960 | 53,806\n| 1970 | 36,764\n| 1980 | 34,926\n| 1990 | 33,287\n| 2000 | 32,485\n| 2010 | 28,690\n|align       = none\n| footnote = \n}}\n==History==\nThe area of present-day Hachimantai was part of ancient [[Mutsu Province]]. The area was dominated by the [[Nanbu clan]] from the early [[Muromachi period]]. During the [[Edo period]] [[Tokugawa shogunate]], the area was under [[Morioka Domain]], and was divided between [[Ninohe District, Iwate|Ninohe District]] in the north and [[Iwate District, Iwate|Iwate District]] in the south.\n\nIn the early [[Meiji period]], the village of Arasawa was created within Ninohe District on April 1, 1889, with the establishment of the modern municipalities system. Arasawa merged with neighboring Tayama Village on September 30, 1956 to form the town of [[Ashiro, Iwate|Ashiro]]. Ashiro was transferred to Iwate District on April 1, 2002.\n\nLikewise, on April 1, 1889, the villages of Tairadate, Obun, Dendo and Terada were established within Kita-Iwate District. Kita-Iwate was merged with Minami-Iwate in 1896. The four villages merged on September 30, 1956 for form the town of [[Nishine, Iwate|Nishine]].\n\nThe city of Hachimantai was established on September 1, 2005, from the merger of the towns of Ashiro and Nishine, and the village of [[Matsuo, Iwate|Matsuo]].\n\n==Government==\nHachimantai has a [[mayor-council]] form of government with a directly elected mayor and a [[unicameral]] city legislature of 22 members.\n\n==Economy==\nThe local economy is based on agriculture, forestry and seasonal tourism.\n\n==Education==\nHachimantai has ten public elementary schools and four public middle schools operated by the city government, and one public high school operated by the Iwate Prefectural Board of Education.\n\n==Transportation==\n===